1. Select a region of the reference (default: full reference).
1. Perform mutational profiling experiments using
- dimethyl sulfate (DMS)
- or SHAPE reagents
- or carbodiimide reagents
1. Quality control the FASTQ file(s) using fastp.
- Trim low-quality base calls.
- Trim adapter sequences.
- Summarize the results in a report file.
1. Determine the relationship between each base call and the
position of the reference to which it aligned.
- Matches, substitutions, and deletions are marked as such.
- Positions next to an insertion are marked with both the side of
the insertion on which they lie (5' or 3') and their own relationship.
- Low-quality base calls are marked as ambiguities.
2. Identify and mark ambiguous insertions and deletions (indels).
- Indels within repetitive sequences have ambiguous locations.
- All possible locations of such indels are marked as ambiguities.
3. Clip bases from both ends of each read.
- Aligning in local mode clips off mutations near the ends of reads.
- As a result, the dataset is biased towards fewer mutations.
- To correct the bias, clip a certain number of bases from both ends
(since the bases at the ends are guaranteed to be matches).
- In pratice, at least 4 nt are clipped from each end; merely for the
purpose of illustration, 1 nt is clipped from each end here.
2. Align reads to reference sequence(s) using Bowtie 2.
- Index the reference sequence(s) automatically.
- Generate one BAM file for each sample.
- Generate a FASTQ file of all reads that did not align.
Note: Mutations near the end of a read will be clipped off when using
local alignment mode (the default).
- Clipping biases the dataset by removing mutations but not matches.
- This bias is corrected during the relate step.
Note: Reads with two mutations separated by fewer than 3 nt are
underrepresented, creating a bias in the mutation rates.
- Correcting the bias involves first masking out any remaining reads
that do happen to have two mutations closer than 3 nt.
- Then the mutation rates are adjusted to what they would have been
if there were no bias reads against reads with two mutations too close.
- Merely for illustration purposes, a minimum gap of 1 nt is used here.
3. Filter out unusable alignments that
- are unmapped or have low mapping quality
- are flagged as secondary/QCfail/duplicate/supplementary
4. Split the sample's BAM file into one BAM file per reference.
- The BAM file takes the name of the reference.
- This format is required by the relate step.
5. (Optional) Separate reads aligning to forward and reverse strands.
- Separation is necessary when RNA in sample contains both strands.
- It is incompatible with non-strand-aware libraries (e.g. RT-PCR).
- This step yields two BAM files per reference.
6. Delete BAM files with too few reads.
- The purpose is to avoid cluttering system with unusable BAM files.
- BAM files with very few reads (< 1,000) are generally unusable.
2. Generate sequencing libraries using
- fragmentation primed with random hexamers or linkers
- RT-PCR (for amplicons targeting a specific sequence)

tspan.tspan: 4. Generate FASTQ files for each sample

text.tspan: 2. Pre-mask unusable positions:
- G and T bases (for DMS)
- poly(A) sequences
- custom positions
2. Cluster the reads to infer alternative
structures present in the RNA ensemble.
For each cluster, calculate:
- its proportion in the ensemble
- the mutation rate at each position
- the probability that each read belongs to it
3. Measure the quality of the clustering:
- Bayesian information criterion (BIC)
- sufficient differences among clusters
- sufficient similarities among repeat trials
- sufficiently small jackpotting quotient
4. Find the optimal number of clusters:
- Increase the number of clusters attempted
and repeat steps 2 and 3.
- Continue until either the BIC does not
decrease or the other quality metrics fail.
1. Group and count reads with identical
- positions of the 5'/3' ends of the read
- positions that are mutated
1. Normalize mutation rates.
- A chosen percentile (e.g. 95th) is set to 1.
- Mutation rates below are scaled linearly.
- Mutation rates above are capped to 1.
2. Model secondary structure(s) using the
Fold program from the RNAstructure suite.
- Fold predicts secondary structures using a
thermodynamic model with a theoretically
correct method of integrating DMS mutation
rates (Cordero et al.).
- Fold outputs structures in CT format.
3. Reformat RNA structures for visualization.
- Rename each RNA structure to include both
its free energy of folding and numerical rank.
- Convert CT into dot-bracket (DB) format.
- Output the normalized mutation rates as a
text file that can be read by VARNA.
3. Choose which types of relationships to count as mutations

tspan.tspan: (default: count substitutions of any base to any other base;
do not count deletions/insertions/ambiguities at any base).

text.tspan: 4. Mask out unusable reads with
- too few non-masked base calls within the region
- too small a ratio of informative to non-masked base calls
- too large a ratio of mutations to informative base calls
- two mutations too close together (default: gap of at least 3 nt)
- discontiguous mates (for paired-end reads only)
5. Mask out unusable positions with
- too few informative base calls
- too large a ratio of mutations to informative base calls
6. Repeat steps 4 and 5 until convergence.
- Masking out positions in step 5 can cause some reads that were kept
in step 4 to no longer pass the filters.
- To solve this inconsistency, repeat steps 4 and 5 until the reads and
positions that are masked stop changing.
